and Λ containing the ordered eigenvalues of ρ,
ER(ρ) = min S(ρ||σ). σ∈D∩MEMS
where MEMS is the class of maximally entangled mixed states.

4

Proof. Deﬁne the following superoperator: T (ρ) = V diag(V †ρV )V †.

Here, diag(ρ) is the superoperator that sets all oﬀdiagonal elements of ρ equal to zero while keeping the diagonal ones intact. This superoperator can also be written as

diag(ρ) = PiρPi/2n,
i

where Pi runs through all possible diagonal matrices having only +1 or −1 on their diagonal [12]. It follows that T

is of the form mentioned in the ﬁrst Lemma and, further-

more, that it is a self-dual superoperator, i.e. T † = T .

It is obvious that all MEMS states (with U1 = U2 = 11)

are left invariant by T . We will now show that any such

T maps separable states to separable states. Consider

thereto the pure product states only; if the proposition

is valid for pure product states, it will be valid for all

separable states (by linearity). The most general pure

product state has the state vector ψ = (ac, ad, bc, bd),

with a, b, c, d complex numbers. Then, since

√

√

V †ψ = ((ad + bc)/ 2, bd, (ad − bc)/ 2, ac),

T (ψψ†) = V diag(V †ψψ†V )V † = V ΛV †,

where the diagonal elements of Λ are, in order, (|(ad + bc)/√2|2, |bd|2, |(ad − bc)/√2|2, |ac|2).

As these values are not necessarily sorted, T (ψψ†) need not be MEMS. However, it is still possible to apply the formula for the negativity of MEMS states which says that

EN (ρ) = max(0, (λ1 − λ3)2 + (λ2 − λ4)2 − λ2 − λ4).

As can be easily checked, the validity of this formula does not rely on the ordering of the λi, as long as each λi pertains to the i-th column of V . In particular, using
λ1 − λ3 = 2ℜ(ab(cd)∗) λ2 ± λ4 = |bd|2 ± |ac|2,
we get for the negativity of T (ψψ†):
EN (T (ψψ†)) = max(0, F )
with

F = (λ1 − λ3)2 + (λ2 − λ4)2 − (λ2 + λ4) = 4ℜ(ab(cd)∗)2 + |bd|4 + |ac|4 − 2|abcd|2 −(|bd|2 + |ac|2)
= |bd|4 + |ac|4 + 2|abcd|2 − 4ℑ(ab(cd)∗)2 −(|bd|2 + |ac|2)
= (|bd|2 + |ac|2)2 − 4ℑ(ab(cd)∗)2 − (|bd|2 + |ac|2) ≤ 0.

Hence, T (ψψ†) is separable, as we set out to prove, so that T maps separable states to separable states.
From the previous discussion it also follows that states of the form V ΛV † are separable if and only if the eigenvalues satisfy

(λ1 − λ3)2 + (λ2 − λ4)2 − λ2 − λ4 ≤ 0

(29)

Furthermore, states V ΛV † are obviously invariant under T . Hence, letting σ traverse all separable states of this form generates the same set of states T (σ) as letting σ traverse all separable states without restriction. Therefore,

ER(ρ)

=

min
σ∈D

S(ρ||σ)

≥ min S(ρ||T (σ))
σ∈D

= min S(ρ||σ).
σ=V ΛV †∈D

Comparing the ﬁrst and the third line, we immediately see that the inequality must be an equality.
Actually, an even stronger result holds, as we can restrict ourselves in this minimization to states σ = V ΛV † ∈ D where the diagonal elements appear in descending order (λ1 ≥ λ2 ≥ λ3 ≥ λ4). In other words, σ may be taken from the set of separable MEMS states. To see this, note that, as ρ and σ are both MEMS,

S(ρ||σ) = pi(lg pi − lg λi),
i
where the pi are the sorted eigenvalues of ρ, and λi are the not necessarily sorted eigenvalues of σ. It is easy to see that one always gets a lower relative entropy by permuting the λi into descending order [12]. This ends the proof of the lemma.
It is now easy to prove the last part of the main theorem: Because the σ are restricted to separable MEMS states, this means that, for any global unitary U , U σU † is still separable. Hence, for ρ ∈ MEMS,
ER(ρ) = min S(ρ||σ) σ∈D∩MEMS
= min S(U ρU †||U σU †) σ∈D∩MEMS
≥ min S(U ρU †||U σU †)
UσU †∈D
= ER(U ρU †),

where the inequality in the penultimate line arises because the minimization domain has been enlarged. Therefore the MEMS states have larger relative entropy of entanglement then all states that can be obtained from it by doing global unitary operations.

